## Standard Execution Flow

1. If the request is Harness installation, upgrade, or migration, use the Harness operations section below instead of the normal feature flow.
2. Confirm the request, scope, and affected files. For non-trivial work, create the task with `harness new-task`; do not copy task templates manually.
3. If the task involves microservices, multi-repo context, external systems, or user-provided external material, read `external-source-intake-standard.md`; create a source pack when needed and project stable facts into `03/04/06`.
4. Create or update `task_plan.md`, `execution_strategy.md`, and `visual_map.md`.
5. Choose the delivery operating model; update Delivery SSoT for team, multi-repo, or shared delivery.
6. If module-parallel is enabled, read `Module-Registry.md`. When a real module exists, maintain `MODULES/<module-key>/brief.md`, `module_plan.md`, `execution_strategy.md`, `visual_map.md`, and `session_prompt.md`; otherwise the dashboard module page is only an inferred task grouping, not a real module plan.
7. If the task may run for a long time, fill `long-running-task-contract.md`.
8. If reviewer, subagent, or release review is required, maintain `review.md`.
9. For merge, PR, CI, or release work, read repo governance and CI/CD standards first.
10. Update Feature SSoT, Delivery SSoT, or Regression SSoT as required by the task.
11. Create the required worktree or record why one is unnecessary.
12. Implement only within the approved scope.
13. Run required checks and capture evidence in `progress.md` or the artifacts index.
14. Before closeout, route required reviews through `review-routing-standard.md` and close blocking findings.
15. Write the walkthrough with task plan, evidence, review result, and residual risk.
16. Run Lessons reflection: create a lesson and update Lessons SSoT when reusable, or record `checked-none: <reason>`.
17. Update Closeout SSoT and Harness Ledger.
18. Clean up worktrees after integration.

## Harness Operations

- New project: diagnose first, choose locale, delivery model, and capabilities; after confirmation run `harness init --locale en-US --capabilities core,... .`.
- Existing v1 Harness update: scan `.harness-capabilities.json` and existing docs first, then use `harness add-capability`; do not overwrite project facts with templates.
- Legacy Harness migration: run `harness status --json .` and `harness migrate-plan --json --limit 1000 .`, recommend baseline-preserve / status-aware-rewrite / full-semantic-rewrite, wait for user confirmation, then write files.
- User-level Skill: use `harness install-user` / `harness doctor-user` only for user agent skill directories; do not commit user-level skill artifacts into the project repo.
- Harness source package maintenance: use `source-package` and `private-harness` profiles only when this repository is the `coding-agent-harness` source package. Normal target projects use `target-project`.

## Harness CLI Entry Points

Before running commands, check `command -v harness`. If the environment does not have `harness`, do not silently install globally.

Ask the user whether this global install is allowed:

```bash
npm install -g coding-agent-harness
```

Explain that it changes the global npm environment and then enables the `harness` command. Run the global install only after explicit user approval.

If the user does not approve or does not respond, run the same command with `npx --yes coding-agent-harness <command>`. The first `npx` run downloads the npm package into local npm cache, but does not write to target project dependencies.

| Scenario | Command |
| --- | --- |
| Create task | `harness new-task <task-id> --title "<title>" --locale en-US .` |
| Create module task | `harness new-task <task-id> --module <module-key> --title "<title>" --locale en-US .` |
| Initialize new Harness | `harness init --locale en-US --capabilities core,dashboard .` |
| Add capability | `harness add-capability <capability> --locale en-US .` |
| Migration plan | `harness migrate-plan --json --limit 1000 .` |
| Migration run / verify | `harness migrate-run --locale en-US --session-dir /tmp/cah-migration --out-dir /tmp/cah-migration/dashboard .` / `harness migrate-verify /tmp/cah-migration/session.json` |
| User-level Skill install / diagnose | `harness install-user --agent codex --global` / `harness doctor-user --agent codex` |
| Record start / log / block / completion | `harness task-start` / `task-log` / `task-block` / `task-complete` |
| Update phase state | `harness task-phase <task-id> <phase-id> --state done --completion 100 --evidence present .` |
| Update module step | `harness module-step <module-key> <step-id> --state done .` |
| Read task index | `harness task-list --json .` |
| Read project status | `harness status --json .` |
| Generate dashboard | `harness dashboard --out-dir /tmp/harness-dashboard .` |
| Check Harness | `harness check --profile target-project .` |
| Maintain Harness source package | `harness check --profile source-package .` |

The CLI is the main entry for task and dashboard data. Edit Markdown directly only for project-specific content the CLI does not own.

## Module Parallel Work

- A module is a real planning object only when `Module-Registry.md` and `MODULES/<module-key>/module_plan.md` exist and are maintained.
- A grouping inferred from task paths or `inferredModule` is not a module plan. The dashboard may show it, but it is not evidence for owner, write scope, or dependency.
- Module workers must read the registry, module plan, module brief, and session prompt before editing.
- Workers update module tasks and `module_plan.md`; only the coordinator or explicit shared-lock owner updates `Module-Registry.md`, Delivery SSoT, Harness Ledger, Closeout SSoT, Regression SSoT, and Cadence Ledger.
- Cross-module or shared-file work must define shared scope, owner, and merge order before workers start.

## Subagent Contract

- Reviewers are read-only unless explicitly assigned a write scope.
- Workers may edit only their assigned worktree, branch, and file scope.
- Worker handoff must include worktree path, branch, commit SHA, checks, changed files, and residual risks.
- The coordinator owns shared ledgers, final integration, and release claims unless delegated in writing.

